<article id="post-1270" class="post-1270 post type-post status-publish format-image hentry category-blog-posts post_format-post-format-image">

	<header class="entry-header">
				<h1 class="entry-title">
			<a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/surviving-freshman-year-like-a-boss/" rel="bookmark">Surviving Freshman Year like a Boss</a>
		</h1>
		
		<div class="entry-meta">
			<span class="post-format"><a class="entry-format" href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/type/image/">Image</a></span><span class="date"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/surviving-freshman-year-like-a-boss/" title="Permalink to Surviving Freshman Year like a Boss" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date published" datetime="2017-02-20T13:30:26+00:00">February 20, 2017</time><time class="updated" datetime="2017-02-20T13:30:47+00:00">February 20, 2017</time></a></span><span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/author/ssrini38/" title="View all posts by ssrini38">ssrini38</a></span>
			
			
		</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
	</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	<div class="entry-content">
		<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1271" src="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/college.png" alt="college" width="261" height="360" /></p>
<p>The huge transition to college life triggers a lot of emotions for many students. Some may feel excited to start this new chapter of their lives, some may feel nervous, and others may be indifferent. I remember riding an emotional roller coaster before starting my undergraduate studies at UIC. I was glad that I (left behind many toxic people in high school) should this be changed to (got to leave high school behind)???, but I also felt very tense about the social, emotional, and academic challenges I would face at UIC. However, after my first semester, all of those tensions have gone away, and I am very content with where I am at in my undergraduate career. Here are four tips that have helped me the most with a smooth transition to college life.</p>
<p><b>Tip 1-Get out of your comfort zone. </b>By getting out of your comfort zone, you will achieve a new perspective on all aspects of life, since you will continuously discover and be exposed to new activities. Furthermore, you will acquire a huge boost in confidence once you accomplish something that you never thought you’d be able to accomplish.</p>
<p><b>Tip 2-Seek help when needed. </b>There will inevitably come a time where you will need help to overcome academic, social, and emotional challenges. Many freshmen feel that they are on their own 100% to deal with these problems. However, it is completely fine to ask for help, and no one should make you feel inferior for seeking help. If you feel yourself getting behind in calculus or struggling with academic writing, then go to office hours. Students often feel intimidated by professors, but they don’t realize that the sole reason for office hours is to seek help or voice any concerns. Moreover, if you are facing emotional or social challenges, there are many resources available at UIC to help you, like the Wellness Center and Counseling Center.</p>
<p><b>Tip 3-Get involved. </b>Since you will be leaving behind old high school friends, getting involved in extracurriculars will immensely help you build connections and strong friendships with other students. You will be able to discover your weaknesses and strengths and likes and dislikes. Additionally, extracurricular activities serve as a great resume-building tool and will tremendously help you land a good job after graduation or even during your undergraduate career.</p>
<p><b>Tip 4-Be good to yourself. </b>It’s so easy to get caught up in exams and other commitments that students often forget to take some time off to relax, and when we fail, we often punish ourselves for not being the best. Being good to yourself will help you accept failure and learn from previous mistakes. So go discover the city with your friends, and go watch a couple of episodes of your favorite TV series. Basically, do whatever makes you happy.</p>
<p>I wish you the very best with your transition to college!</p>
<p>By: Fatima Ahmad</p>
			</div><!-- .entry-content -->

	
</article><!-- #post-## -->

			
				
<article id="post-1265" class="post-1265 post type-post status-publish format-image hentry category-blog-posts post_format-post-format-image">

	<header class="entry-header">
				<h1 class="entry-title">
			<a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/my-life-with-an-autistic-sibling-worthy-lessons-that-ive-learned/" rel="bookmark">My Life with an Autistic Sibling: Worthy Lessons that I&#8217;ve Learned</a>
		</h1>
		
		<div class="entry-meta">
			<span class="post-format"><a class="entry-format" href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/type/image/">Image</a></span><span class="date"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/my-life-with-an-autistic-sibling-worthy-lessons-that-ive-learned/" title="Permalink to My Life with an Autistic Sibling: Worthy Lessons that I&#8217;ve Learned" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date published" datetime="2017-01-11T15:40:12+00:00">January 11, 2017</time></a></span><span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/author/ssrini38/" title="View all posts by ssrini38">ssrini38</a></span>
			
			
		</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
	</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	<div class="entry-content">
		<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1266 aligncenter" src="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/image-4-1.jpg" alt="image (4) (1)" width="600" height="600" /></p>
<p>My 21-year-old brother was diagnosed with Autism Spectrum Disorder when he was around two and a half years old. My parents noticed his impaired speech; he slowly stopped communicating and using words that a typical three-year-old would use. After his speech loss, he has been very dependent. He has been unable to function in daily life activities, like basic housekeeping, without a tremendous amount of aid from others. Currently, he is learning to communicate through iPad applications, and he is enrolled in a special education program that provides training in vocational skills.</p>
<p>My brother’s condition has influenced me in a lot of ways. I have gone through plenty of emotional burdens and many what-if scenarios in my head. It hurts me to see the occasional body language, from strangers and even some family members, that judges his atypical behavior. It frustrates me to see him cry or have a meltdown, since I feel so helpless. There are many nights when I just wonder &#8211; what if my friends backbite about him? What if no one would want to marry me because of him? What does his future hold for him? What would life be like if he wasn’t autistic, or if I didn’t have a brother at all?</p>
<p>Even though life with an autistic brother is challenging, he has taught me valuable life lessons. Watching my brother’s struggle with basic communication, I have learned always to be grateful and to never take life for granted. I am grateful to go to an amazing school in the city and to be able to interact with all my peers. I have also learned to have patience from his sporadic behavior. Instead of worrying about what others think, I concentrate on what I can do as a sister to make him feel better. Most importantly, I am learning to become a strong person. Without a doubt, my brother’s condition has created some hurdles for our family to overcome. However, we have been able to work through all of them by having strong and encouraging attitudes. Likewise, I am confident that by the time I graduate, I will be strong enough to overcome any curveballs thrown at me in my professional career.</p>
<p>By: Fatima Ahmad</p>
			</div><!-- .entry-content -->

	
</article><!-- #post-## -->

			
				
<article id="post-1258" class="post-1258 post type-post status-publish format-image hentry category-blog-posts post_format-post-format-image">

	<header class="entry-header">
				<h1 class="entry-title">
			<a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/finals-week/" rel="bookmark">Finals Week</a>
		</h1>
		
		<div class="entry-meta">
			<span class="post-format"><a class="entry-format" href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/type/image/">Image</a></span><span class="date"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/finals-week/" title="Permalink to Finals Week" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date published" datetime="2016-12-06T22:54:14+00:00">December 6, 2016</time><time class="updated" datetime="2016-12-06T23:01:22+00:00">December 6, 2016</time></a></span><span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/author/ssrini38/" title="View all posts by ssrini38">ssrini38</a></span>
			
			
		</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
	</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	<div class="entry-content">
		<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1259 aligncenter" src="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/Screen-Shot-2016-12-06-at-4.51.08-PM.png" alt="Screen Shot 2016-12-06 at 4.51.08 PM" width="298" height="203" /></p>
<p><strong>Five Tips: How To Survive Finals Week</strong><br />
<strong>By:  Polina Gubareva</strong></p>
<p>No matter what major or year in school you are, I know that you may feel the pressure of finals week creeping up on you. Even though everyone is different, we can all agree that two goals to have during this time would be success and a low stress level.</p>
<p>As a junior, I have gathered these five tips on how to accomplish these goals:</p>
<p>#1: Sleep</p>
<p>I know. Starting off with this is totally expected, but sleep is one of the most important things you can do for yourself during finals week. Some people may claim to be able to function on three or four hours of sleep, but most of us need our solid seven or eight hours. If you plan your sleep ahead of time, you may find that it will help you study better because your mind will be well-rested. So, even though you are giving time towards sleep, the time you use to study will be more efficient.</p>
<p>#2: Eat Healthy</p>
<p>Even though junk food is fast, easy, and gives you energy quickly, it is damaging to your health in the long run and is actually not helping your memory! Try to switch out junk food with alternatives like fruits, vegetables, or even smoothies. Keep in mind, you can still treat yourself to carbohydrates and sweets, but keep it in moderation.</p>
<p>#3: Use Your Resources</p>
<p>UIC and the Honors College have plenty of recourses designed to help students succeed and keep stress and anxiety to a minimum. Make full use of the Honors College student tutors. Go see your personal Honors College advisor, and explore places like the Science Learning Center, the Math Learning Center, and the Writing Center. In addition, visit the Wellness Center if you need to talk to someone about your stress or anxiety.</p>
<p>#4: Don’t Procrastinate</p>
<p>Even though the new seasons coming out on Netflix look tempting, make sure you get a head start on knowing what you need to study for each final, and take the time to manage your time evenly among all of your subjects. It may even help to make your own schedule, but make sure to include small study breaks, when you can eat a healthy snack, exercise, rest, or indulge in an episode or two of your favorite show.</p>
<p>#5: Be Selfish</p>
<p>It is easy to get caught up in helping others, or in socializing with friend groups that may have different course loads. I have friends that get upset with me during finals week because I tend to put my social life to the side and zone in on my work. I’m not saying to completely ignore everybody, but instead to be smart with your time. For example, instead of going out to dinner with your friends, take a rain check until finals are over, but still keep in touch with them during your study breaks.</p>
<p>All in all, in order to succeed during finals week, make sure that you stay positive and never stop pushing towards your goal. And remember, after that week is over, we get a whole month of winter break! Good luck and study hard!</p>
<p><strong>How to Get Through Finals<br />
</strong><strong>By: Dyese Moody</strong></p>
<p>There’s one thing that probably scares students more than having to worry about loans and financial aid. Finals. You say goodbye to your social life, your sleep, and your sanity for a week. As much as we might despise their existence, we can’t escape their wrath on our grade in a class, which then affects our overly sensitive GPAs. The best part of finals is not when you finally finish taking them, but when you get the grades back. Here are some tips that I have for getting through finals:</p>
<p>#1:  How to Study</p>
<p>Set up a reasonable schedule to study for each course. Don’t dedicate five hours to studying for a course you don’t have trouble with. For example, I’ll spend one hour on psychology each day and four hours on organic chemistry because I understand psychology much better than organic chemistry.</p>
<p>#2: Can I Take a Break?</p>
<p>Take short breaks in between your hours of studying; it won’t kill you or your grade to take a break. Don’t study for five hours straight! Take a five-15 minute break for each hour you study and/or when you switch the subject you are studying.</p>
<p>#3: Food</p>
<p>Don’t forget to eat. You actually need sustenance to function.</p>
<p>#4: Alone or in a Group?</p>
<p>Try to have a study group for classes that are difficult for you. It’s beneficial to have someone there to talk out problems or topics that you may not understand or vice-versa. Also, it’s great to see that you aren’t suffering alone.</p>
<p>#5: Sleep</p>
<p>At least try to get a solid eight hours of sleep before you take your exam. Taking an exam while you’re exhausted is the worst because it’s easier for you to lose focus, mix up information, or misinterpret questions.</p>
<p>#6: Me Time</p>
<p>Take 30 minutes to an hour to do something for yourself that doesn’t involve schoolwork.</p>
<p>#7: Motivation</p>
<p>Find a quote, video, song, or something to keep you calm before your exam, hype you up to take your exam, or convince you that you will be fine when you take the exam.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
			</div><!-- .entry-content -->

	
</article><!-- #post-## -->

			
				
<article id="post-1240" class="post-1240 post type-post status-publish format-image hentry category-blog-posts post_format-post-format-image">

	<header class="entry-header">
				<h1 class="entry-title">
			<a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/what-i-learned-from-the-asda-national-leadership-conference-2016/" rel="bookmark">What I Learned from the ASDA National Leadership Conference 2016 </a>
		</h1>
		
		<div class="entry-meta">
			<span class="post-format"><a class="entry-format" href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/type/image/">Image</a></span><span class="date"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/what-i-learned-from-the-asda-national-leadership-conference-2016/" title="Permalink to What I Learned from the ASDA National Leadership Conference 2016 " rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date published" datetime="2016-11-19T20:15:28+00:00">November 19, 2016</time><time class="updated" datetime="2017-01-11T15:41:53+00:00">January 11, 2017</time></a></span><span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/author/ssrini38/" title="View all posts by ssrini38">ssrini38</a></span>
			
			
		</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
	</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	<div class="entry-content">
		<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1241 aligncenter" src="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/10422491_1789636241324317_34649105466443536_n-1.jpg" alt="10422491_1789636241324317_34649105466443536_n (1)" width="720" height="960" /></p>
<p>The American Student Dental Association (ASDA) is a widely known organization for dental and pre-dental students. Once a year, they hold a national leadership conference right here in Chicago, at the Hilton Hotel. I had an amazing experience attending this conference this year, and I hope to share a few things I took away from it.</p>
<p>The conference is separated into different topics ranging from pre-dental issues, leadership, career planning, personal development, and ASDA Chapter Management.</p>
<p>I chose to attend mostly pre-dental activities, which included workshops on how to write a personal statement, a mock interview process, a panel of admissions directors (including UIC College of Dentistry’s Director of Admissions, Carolyn Feller!), and even a workshop on how to expand and strengthen a Pre-Dental Club. In addition, I attended a few wellness lectures, one of which was led by our very own Johanna Strokoff, who is a psychologist at UIC. She taught us how to recognize and overcome the negative effects of stress. Also, I attended a program regarding women in dentistry. It was a panel of three very accomplished dentists who truly inspired me and only made my passion for dentistry stronger.</p>
<p>To my surprise, I was the <em>only</em> student from UIC representing the pre-dental population. How could this be? We are located only blocks away from this conference, while other students had to fly in from other states. Our accessibility to the city offers us many opportunities and resources, and I learned we should not take this for granted.</p>
<p>As an active member of the Pre-Dental Club here at UIC, I am hoping to organize a time for me to talk to my peers during a general meeting to teach them about what I learned, get more people involved with ASDA itself, and actually utilize the amazing opportunities it provides for us.</p>
<p>I also learned that these conferences are monumentally important no matter what career plan you may have. They allow you to learn from your peers and potential future dental school classmates. Also, it is not only important to attend these types of conferences but also to take the information back home and convey it to others.</p>
<p>With this comes the notion of leadership. One of my favorite quotes at the conference was as follows:</p>
<p>“Leadership is a skill that can be learned. It is a beneficial influence on others, and it’s a service,&#8221; said Dr. Gabe Holdwick.</p>
<p>Being a part of the Honors College instills this sort of passion in me to be a leader, to help those around me, and to positively influence my community. I felt that connection the entire time I was at the conference, and I represented UIC and the Honors College proudly.</p>
<p>If you are not a pre-dental student, I hope that reading about this motivates you to venture out of your comfort zone, join an organization that you have a passion for, and begin to network and immerse yourself into what you love as much as you can.</p>
<p>By: Polina Gubareva</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
			</div><!-- .entry-content -->

	
</article><!-- #post-## -->

			
				
<article id="post-954" class="post-954 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-blog-posts category-student-focus">

	<header class="entry-header">
				<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/947/" rel="bookmark"></a></h1>
		
				<div class="entry-meta">
			<span class="date"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/947/" title="Permalink to " rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date published" datetime="2015-12-04T18:50:56+00:00">December 4, 2015</time></a></span><span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/author/slee355/" title="View all posts by slee355">slee355</a></span>
			
			
		</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	
		<div class="entry-content">
		<h1 style="text-align: center"><b>Running for Me, Running for Them</b></h1>
<p style="text-align: center"><a href="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/HC15_2015.jpg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-948" src="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/HC15_2015.jpg" alt="HC15_2015" width="390" height="292" /></a></p>
<p>In August, I made a very big decision: to be healthy and active. After years of telling myself I would do so, I never really changed my habits. My family history of diabetes and high blood pressure was scary, yet I was going down the same path with my diet of pudding and cookies. But during the summer, I decided that enough was enough. I needed to change. The greatest struggle with this change was converting my internal desire to an actual behavior; my abstract idea of “health” needed a concrete goal. As a result, I challenged myself to run the Hot Chocolate 15K race in Chicago.</p>
<p>With my objective set, I started training every day. I spent time reading about running programs, muscle workout programs, calorie counting, and proper stretches to minimize injury. With my brother’s guidance, I created a workout plan and started running.</p>
<p>As school started and my academic workload increased, I prioritized my running and my eating schedule. Instead of ordering pizza or just snacking on cookies, I made sure that I ate something healthier (like salad or a peanut butter sandwich and yogurt). I reduced my procrastinating habits because I had to make time for running. I focused myself on my goal and knew that I would rather be running than wasting my time.</p>
<p>My decision to be healthy was not simply a change in eating habits. It was a change in my lifestyle and my priorities. I learned to be more disciplined with my time. For the first time in my life, I concentrated only on my needs and my time in order to be the most balanced person I could be. Throughout my life, I’ve found my identity in my friends and family; this time, I sought my identity from myself as a student and runner.</p>
<p>As race day approached in November, I continued to train, working on my physical and mental endurance. Running 15K (9.3 miles) was not going to be easy—my knees and feet would probably hurt and I may become discouraged running for over an hour with the finish line still another half hour away. But as it turned out, these thoughts didn’t come to mind during the race. I was buzzing with energy on race day, but I still paced myself throughout the race, never running too fast to lose my breath. My goal was to keep running and never stop to walk,, even when I was going uphill or felt tired.</p>
<p>And I did it! I ran the entire race at a steady pace of 10:50 min/mile, completing the race in 1 hour and 40 minutes!</p>
<p>Now, even with the run completed, I plan to continue making healthy choices and being active, even if it’s something as simple as taking the stairs and eating a banana over a Snickers bar. It’s the small things that really add up. However, it would be wrong to say that my training and discipline was the sole reason of my success. The training definitely gave me the confidence to run the race, but without the support of my family and my friends, I would have easily given up. Some of my friends drove a long distance to support me, holding posters and cheering me on while I ran; other friends were volunteering and cheered me on, motivating me to keep going. This was a constant reminder to never stop running—I wanted to make myself proud, and I wanted them to them to be proud of me.</p>
<p>While I started this race for myself and for my health, I finished this race because of the friendship and support I have in my life. It is this love and encouragement that drives me each day to keep working hard.</p>
<p>Honors Ambassador Blogger: Nidhi Kadakia</p>
			</div><!-- .entry-content -->
	
	
