<article id="post-944" class="post-944 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-blog-posts category-student-focus">

	<header class="entry-header">
				<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/944/" rel="bookmark"></a></h1>
		
				<div class="entry-meta">
			<span class="date"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/944/" title="Permalink to " rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date published" datetime="2015-11-26T13:50:32+00:00">November 26, 2015</time></a></span><span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/author/slee355/" title="View all posts by slee355">slee355</a></span>
			
			
		</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	
		<div class="entry-content">
		<h1 style="text-align: center"><b>Volunteering: (Not) Going for the Glory</b></h1>
<p style="text-align: center"><a href="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/imd-guest-house-baking.jpg"><img class="wp-image-945 aligncenter" src="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/imd-guest-house-baking.jpg" alt="imd guest house baking" width="350" height="339" /></a></p>
<p>There are a lot of things we try to cram into four short years of undergraduate life: research, student organizations, social experiences, and more. It’s hard sometimes to balance a heavy load of coursework along with all the extra commitments that college students often take on. But at the same time, I feel like many college students—stressed as they might be—miss out on one of the most important and rewarding extracurriculars: volunteering.</p>
<p>It can be intimidating to search for interesting volunteer opportunities in the city; after all, Chicago is a big place, and there are countless options available. But what seems daunting is actually a blessing in disguise. With so many opportunities, there’s bound to be an activity or interest for everybody. Often times, there are a number of volunteering opportunities offered by student organizations, and it’s easy to get involved in something that excites you, such as volunteering to hand out water at a marathon or to walk dogs at a local shelter. In the past semester, I’ve gone with friends to package food at Feed my Starving Children in Schaumburg, helped to cheer on walkers at Step Out: Walk to Stop Diabetes alongside the UIC Association of Pre-Medical Students, and volunteered with the Vietnamese Student Association at the Hot Chocolate Run, among others. No two volunteer events have been the same, but each feels equally as worthwhile and rewarding.</p>
<p>While on-campus activities, such as research or joining clubs are integral parts of the overall UIC experience too, there’s something about the feeling of personally impacting other people through individual interactions at volunteer events.   Looking for a chance to do this? Think about going over to the Illinois Medical District Guest House and baking muffins for the families of patients seeking treatment there. The last time I did, I talked to several different people and learned their stories; most of them have travelled from out of state to seek treatment in Chicago, and one man told me that living at the IMD Guest House helped him feel like he wasn’t on his own in this big city. Or maybe consider helping out with pet therapy at the Lakeview Nursing and Rehabilitation Centre—you don’t even need to have a pet to volunteer! Volunteering is not only fun and a good way to get out and explore Chicago, but it’s also a great feeling to meet new people and realize that you can make their day a little bit better.</p>
<p>(photo is courtesy of IMD Guest House Foundation)</p>
<p>Honors Ambassador Blogger: Nikita Pillai</p>
			</div><!-- .entry-content -->
	
	
