<article id="post-940" class="post-940 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-blog-posts category-student-focus">

	<header class="entry-header">
				<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/940/" rel="bookmark"></a></h1>
		
				<div class="entry-meta">
			<span class="date"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/940/" title="Permalink to " rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date published" datetime="2015-11-17T23:23:03+00:00">November 17, 2015</time></a></span><span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/author/slee355/" title="View all posts by slee355">slee355</a></span>
			
			
		</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	
		<div class="entry-content">
		<h1 style="text-align: center"><b>Tips for College: Staying Productive and Happy</b></h1>
<p style="text-align: center"><a href="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Adil-Blog-1-pic.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-941 aligncenter" src="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/Adil-Blog-1-pic.jpg" alt="Adil Blog 1 pic" width="442" height="442" /></a></p>
<p>College is a place where we have the ability to reevaluate and build upon ourselves both academically and personally. College is truly a land of opportunity, which should be taken as a privilege by students.</p>
<p>College has been an enlightening experience for me, and here is some of what I’ve learned:</p>
<ol>
<li>You can’t change what you like:</li>
</ol>
<p>It is generally known that many students tend to select high-paying or “safe” careers, as they don’t want to risk their futures. However, from what I have seen around me, my friends who have followed their passions tend to be much happier than those who are pressured into certain paths.</p>
<ol start="2">
<li>Participate, and get involved around campus:</li>
</ol>
<p>College can offer several opportunities for you to explore. Maybe you like art? Or have a passion for public speaking? Organizations and other extracurricular activities can offer you opportunities to learn more about specific interests and maybe discover something new about yourself &#8212; and this is not a bad thing. Some tend to believe that participating in activities unrelated to their major and profession goals can hurt them, but this is absolutely incorrect. Involvement in a diverse set of activities, whether educational or social, can always be beneficial, as knowledge comes in many shapes and forms. It is our duty as students to explore those “if’s” and “what’s” in order to gain a more enriching, holistic perspective.</p>
<ol start="3">
<li>Manage your academic life with your social life :</li>
</ol>
<p>College can definitely get stressful and lead to us not having time to socialize. Don’t do this. The best way to manage the workload and the social sphere of your everyday life is to procrastinate less and do your work on time. This will allow you the liberty of making friends without having to sacrifice your academic excellence. And believe me when I say this: friends are a crucial part of your life; they are the ones who will be there when you’re panicking after an organic chemistry exam or when you need any sort of moral and emotional support. They will help you grow as a student and develop into the human being you aspire to become, all while also making memorable moments along the way.</p>
<p>These are my tips for surviving college and enjoying it. Always remember college is a privilege, so don’t take it for granted. Use it to better yourself and the community around you.</p>
<p>Honors Ambassador Blogger: Adil Siddique</p>
			</div><!-- .entry-content -->
	
	
</article><!-- #post-## -->

			
				
<article id="post-935" class="post-935 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-blog-posts category-student-focus">

	<header class="entry-header">
				<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/935/" rel="bookmark"></a></h1>
		
				<div class="entry-meta">
			<span class="date"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/935/" title="Permalink to " rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date published" datetime="2015-10-28T19:44:58+00:00">October 28, 2015</time></a></span><span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/author/slee355/" title="View all posts by slee355">slee355</a></span>
			
			
		</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	
		<div class="entry-content">
		<h1 style="text-align: center"><b>From Rural to Urban: How to Adjust to Life in the City</b></h1>
<p><a href="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/DSCN2320.jpg"><img class="wp-image-936 aligncenter" src="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/DSCN2320.jpg" alt="DSCN2320" width="612" height="344" /></a></p>
<p><em>            What animals do you raise?</em></p>
<p><em>            Have you ever driven a tractor?</em></p>
<p><em>            Do you like country music?</em></p>
<p><em>            What do you do for fun in a rural area?</em></p>
<p><em>            Where is Carthage, Illinois anyway?</em></p>
<p>As a UIC student raised in rural Illinois, I often receive questions similar to the previous list. Many of my fellow classmates are unaware of what it is like to live in a rural community and the culture it entails. Similarly, when I first came to Chicago two years ago as a freshman, I had no idea how different living in the city would be. I knew that there would be tall skyscrapers, heavy traffic, and sights to see. However, I was unaware of the blend of cultures, driven leaders, and amazing opportunities that the city had to offer. Although I have only lived in Chicago for two years, I feel like I have done a great job of establishing a life here and can confidently say that I made the right choice by selecting UIC for my undergraduate education.</p>
<p>While I am more than settled into the Chicagoan lifestyle, there are still times when I feel nostalgia for my previous life. Sometimes I crave the golden fields of harvest, the scent of a gentle breeze coming off the wild grasses, and the serenity of a walk through the woods. There are days when I miss the culture that I spent 18 years of my life partaking in. And like anyone, there are days when the longing for my family and childhood friends is difficult to bear. This feeling of nostalgia is commonly felt among college students, but can be especially difficult for those students who live farther away from their homes and are experiencing living in the city for the first time. At times it may even seem like there is no one else who understands this specific kind of homesickness.</p>
<p>The good news is that there are many places to go, people to talk to, and things you can do if you ever find yourself feeling this way. As an Honors College student, you can always feel free to speak with your Honors College Advisor or even your Honors College Ambassador about your concerns and what you can do to overcome them. Additionally, there are many other places to go on campus if you need help, such as the Counseling Center or to campus housing staff if you live in the dorms.</p>
<p>As a student who has battled the challenges of adjusting to the fast-paced culture of the city, I want to give a few bits of advice to those who may be currently going through the same struggle. This advice stems from my own personal experience as a rural student adapting to life in Chicago and at UIC.</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Accept and embrace the changes that come with moving to a large city.</strong> You will experience new cultures, beliefs, and ideas that are different than what you were used to in your rural community. Keep your mind open and take in as much as you can! (As Dorothy put it, “Toto, I’ve a feeling we are not in Kansas anymore.”)</li>
</ol>
<ol start="2">
<li><strong>Do well in your classes.</strong> Remember one of the main reasons that you are at UIC is to get an education. You will feel better about yourself and more connected to the university when you are accomplishing the educational goals you have set for yourself.</li>
</ol>
<ol start="3">
<li><strong>Join organizations you feel passionate about. </strong>The more involved you are with organizations, the more you will feel tied to the university. It doesn’t matter what kind (volunteer, cultural, academic, sport, or leisure) you pick, as joining any organization will motivate you towards reaching new goals. Additionally, if you find an organization that represents your interests, you will be more likely to find people with similar views as yourself and make more connections.</li>
</ol>
<ol start="4">
<li><strong>Find people with common interests. </strong>It is important to find people who you can relate to and feel comfortable around. These are also the people who will go on adventures with you and cheer you up when you are having a rough day. I would never had made it in the city without the incredible friends I made during my first two years!</li>
</ol>
<ol start="5">
<li><strong>Explore the city as much as possible. </strong>There are so many places to go, sites to see, and food to eat. Some of my favorite memories stem from venturing into the city with friends. A few things I would encourage are: eating a gyro in Greektown, sunbathing at Oak Street Beach, riding the slides at Maggie Daley Park (even if you’re over the age limit), attending Festa Italiana, ice skating in Millennium Park, and visiting the many museums on free admission days. I would also encourage you to check out the Chicago Signature Honors Programming for other exciting events to experience! (https://chicagosignature.honors.uic.edu/ ) There is so much to do, but you must actively pursue it!</li>
</ol>
<ol start="6">
<li><strong>Don’t go home too often.</strong> It is difficult to develop a new life at your college when you continually return to and stay attached to your old life. It is important to stay at school when you have free time to develop new relationships and build memories. This can be especially difficult at first, but it does get easier with time.</li>
</ol>
<ol start="7">
<li><strong>Realize that you can go home if you need to. </strong>Although I recommended not going home frequently, it is important to remember that if you get in a slump and become homesick, you can always arrange a trip home. Don’t bottle up your homesickness until it is unbearable. Sometimes, time at home is just what we need to rejuvenate. (I personally go home about once a month.)</li>
</ol>
<ol start="8">
<li><strong>Use Skype/Facetime to stay in touch with family and friends. </strong>With today’s technology, it is easier than ever to stay in contact with people over long distances. Use these tools to call your family and friends and share with them all of your amazing adventures at UIC.</li>
</ol>
<ol start="9">
<li><strong>Be proud of your heritage and share your own background knowledge and experiences with others</strong>. It is important that you take in and learn from others about life in the city. However, it is also important to share your own experiences and culture that you have from living in a rural community. It can be beneficial to show others who you are and what matters to you. It is this exchange of ideas from the diverse groups we have that make UIC such an amazing institution! Realize that you are important and have valuable information to contribute!</li>
</ol>
<p>As a rural student at UIC, you have the amazing opportunity to experience both the rural and urban ways of life. You have the ability to be a rural diplomat when in the city, and an urban diplomat when you return home. It can be difficult to adjust to the changes, but if you are able to stick with it, it can have an amazing impact on your life. I can assuredly say that it has changed me for the better.</p>
<p><em>Answers to opening questions:</em></p>
<ol>
<li><em>Cows</em></li>
<li><i>Yes</i></li>
<li><em>Of course ( &lt;3 Carrie Underwood)</em></li>
<li><em>Gardening, bonfires, mushroom hunting, trapshooting</em></li>
<li><em>Western Illinois near Iowa and Missouri border</em></li>
</ol>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Honors Ambassador Blogger: Alex N. Ourth</p>
			</div><!-- .entry-content -->
	
	
