<article id="post-926" class="post-926 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-blog-posts category-student-focus">

	<header class="entry-header">
				<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/926/" rel="bookmark"></a></h1>
		
				<div class="entry-meta">
			<span class="date"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/926/" title="Permalink to " rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date published" datetime="2015-10-21T21:24:32+00:00">October 21, 2015</time></a></span><span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/author/slee355/" title="View all posts by slee355">slee355</a></span>
			
			
		</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	
		<div class="entry-content">
		<h1 style="text-align: center"><b>Navratri: The Most Wonderful Time of the Year!</b></h1>
<p><a href="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Garba2015NK.jpg"><img class="wp-image-927 aligncenter" src="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Garba2015NK.jpg" alt="Garba2015NK" width="294" height="523" /></a></p>
<p>Bells tinkling, skirts swaying, bangles jangling, earrings twinkling…Navratri is my favorite time of the year!</p>
<p>Navratri, an important Hindu holiday, is celebrated for nine days every year beginning sometime in October. This year, Navratri was celebrated from October 13-21. Literally translating to “nine nights,” this holiday honors nine goddesses of the Hindu faith—one on each night of the celebration. These goddesses symbolize female strength, faith, and discipline. We pray to them as they deliver courage and hope to overcome obstacles. While my largest obstacles during this time are my impending midterms and papers, the goddesses give me strength—perhaps in the form of coffee! —to stay up late to study.</p>
<p>To celebrate Navratri, an altar is placed on the center of the floor and decorated with a goddess. Around this altar, men, women, and children dressed in traditional clothing perform a traditional folk dance, <em>garba. </em>At one side, musicians sing folk music and play their various instruments. Dancers form concentric circles around the altar, with each circle following a different variation of garba. The older generation may perform a simpler, three-step garba, while the younger generations dance more intricate, fast-paced steps. In any case, this dance can be done in any form and at any speed.</p>
<p>When I dance, I lose myself in the music, in the atmosphere, and in my worship. This holiday gives me an opportunity to celebrate my heritage and my devotion. Though I’ve grown up in the United States, I eagerly anticipate this holiday each year, putting on my anklets and picking out my dresses and jewelry well in advance. I even give up my procrastinating habits, getting my work done early so that I can go dance on Fridays and Saturdays.</p>
<p>My mom tells me that since I could walk, I’ve been dancing garba. In India, Navratri is only celebrated for nine days; but in the United States, garbas are held on most weekends throughout October and even into early November. My weekends have been booked for the next month!</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Honors Ambassador Blogger: Nidhi Kadakia</p>
			</div><!-- .entry-content -->
	
	
</article><!-- #post-## -->

			
				
<article id="post-903" class="post-903 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-blog-posts category-student-focus">

	<header class="entry-header">
				<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/903/" rel="bookmark"></a></h1>
		
				<div class="entry-meta">
			<span class="date"><a href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/903/" title="Permalink to " rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date published" datetime="2015-10-06T16:09:22+00:00">October 6, 2015</time></a></span><span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/author/slee355/" title="View all posts by slee355">slee355</a></span>
			
			
		</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	
		<div class="entry-content">
		<h1 style="text-align: center"><b>Get Up and Grab a Hat!</b></h1>
<p><a href="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/pillaiphoto1-2.jpg"><img class="wp-image-904 aligncenter" src="http://ampersand.honors.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/pillaiphoto1-2.jpg" alt="pillaiphoto1 (2)" width="588" height="392" /></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>It’s easy to let yourself get pigeonholed in college.</p>
<p>People often preach the importance of finding research or getting an internship. They tell students that they need to join clubs and make connections, work towards furthering themselves in their career fields and most importantly, <em>stay focused.</em></p>
<p>I took that information to heart as a freshman in the Honors College, and tried to do all the things that older students had told me were important as a pre-med student: I found a position as a research assistant, joined the Society of Future Physicians, and was even looking into volunteering at a city hospital. And I don’t regret any of it, because I’ve made friends and had wonderful opportunities to explore my future career field alongside other students who are working towards goals similar to mine.</p>
<p>But then I decided that I needed to slow down and take a moment to do something different.</p>
<p>It started when my friend dragged me to a Vietnamese Student Association meeting—and it ended with me performing traditional hat dance as a member of their cultural dance team.</p>
<p>It’s important to note that I didn’t drop everything that I had already established. I still went to physician lectures at SFP, I still conducted research on the correlation between capillary blood flow in the eyes and heart disease, and I still enjoyed it all. My career-focused activities were a huge part of my school year, and I’m glad for all the invaluable experiences they’ve provided me, but I’m also glad that I didn’t spend all year trying to think of ways to prepare myself for graduate school.</p>
<p>Cultural dance was not only an escape from the more academic-oriented portions of my life, but it was also a way for me to experience a totally different culture, meet people I would have never met if I stuck only to pre-med associations. Most importantly, it was an experience I never thought I’d have in college.</p>
<p>I never would have imagined that I could be standing center-stage in the Forum, wearing a long, traditional áo dai and carrying a wide bamboo hat. I never could have seen myself performing in different venues all around the city at traditional Vietnamese New Year celebrations. I never anticipated having such a good time at VSA (I’m not even Vietnamese, for the record), and I’m so glad I was wrong.</p>
<p>As students, we need to work hard; that’s a given. We need to work to further our interests and meet our goals, to gain experience now that’ll be valuable in our careers later—but we also need to have fun. People will tell you how to beef up your resume and get the most out of your courses, but not enough people will tell you to go out and try something new.</p>
<p>And what better time to do it than now?</p>
<p>Honors Ambassador Blogger: Nikita Pillai</p>
			</div><!-- .entry-content -->
	
	
</article><!-- #post-## -->

			
